General Comments:
One of the  challenges I had was dealing with the provided printHeader.c file. 
It used hardcoded pointer arithmetic (+15, +30, +45) to print the category names. 
Initially, reading the categories as a single string caused garbage data to print 
because the offsets jumped into uninitialized memory. I had to refactor the
function to parse the categories individually and space them exactly 15 
bytes apart using memset() and strcpy().

GDB Debugging Report:
I used gdb to investigate why my category headers were printing strange characters
and causing alignment issues. I compiled with the -g flag, started gdb, and set a breakpoint 
at the printHeader() function call. When I used the print command to inspect the 
Category_Names string and examined the memory specifically at (char*)Category_Names+15
and (char*)Category_Names+30, I found that they contained uninitialized garbage values 
instead of the expected category words.